Denote by (\alpha) the part {(1 + \omega^k + \omega^{2k} + \omega^{3k})^{-1}
| k = 1, 2, \ldots, 1728\}. Note
that \[\sum_{k = 1}^{1728} (1 + \omega^k + \omega^{2k} + \omega^{3k})^{-1} =
\sum_{m = 0}^{1728-1} \rho(m),\] where \'][\[\rho(m) = \begin{cases}
4/k & (k | m, k \ne 0) \\\ 0 & (k \nmid m). \end{cases}][\]
Now if we add the 1729-th roots of unity, we have \[\sum_{m = 0}^{1728}
\rho(m) = \frac{1}{4} \sum_{m = 0}^{1728} \sum_{\substack{k | m}} k = \frac{1}{4} \sum_{k = 1}^{1728} k \cdot \sigma_0(k).\]
On the other hand, we have \[\sum_{m = 0}^{1728} \rho(m) = (1 + 1729) + (1729 + 1) = 3460.\]
So \[\sum_{k = 1}^{1728} k \cdot \sigma_0(k) = \boxed{13840}.\][/think]
